Hi, Graeme.

As Graeme wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/18/2004 at 10:10:07 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Use the method of cylindrical shells to find the volume of the solid 
>formed by revolving the region bounded by the graph of y=2x^2-4x+5, 
>the x-axis, and the lines x=2 and x=3, about the line x=1.
>
>[Difficulty]
>I find the washer/disc method ok, but I am not quite grasping this 
>new method.  Setting up the integral is the difficult part, the 
>solving of the integral is fine.
>
>[Thoughts]
>I have worked this question out to: V=2pi(definite integral of (2,3))
>[(1-x)(2x^2-4x+5)]dx which gives me -24pi.  Obviously this isn't 
>correct, but I believe the integral is.

The sign error is in setting up the integral. The integrand should be 
2*pi*r*h where r is the radius of the cylindrical shell and h is its 
height. You've got the radius as (1-x). However, with x between 2 and 
3, this gives a negative radius! You should have r = (x-1). That will 
fix everything.

